The Ebola Epidemic. We have lost about 4000 lives because of this disease, while it may have resulted in several social changes we can surely say that our economy remained substantially the same. Tourists and companies are still showing interest in our country. Nevertheless, Ebola formed a huge obstacle for all commercial business on different levels. There is also no denying that the country’s agricultural sector was very strongly affected, starting with the decrease in harvests (2.8% because of a decline in both vegetables and rice production), to the reduction in the livestock (with 24% fewer chickens in the country) and the closure of the fishery sector. With regards to the businesses, big companies suffered the largest impact due to long shut downs. Many exporters suffered reduced receipts in foreign currency, while small and mediumsized enterprises also felt the crisis in terms of less production and reduced revenues.

Sierra Leone still lingers in an economic recession with very low growth rates and public expenditures are limited by the scarce resources. Although agriculture and fisheries still represent one of the main sectors in the country, this sector has not fully recovered from the Ebola Epidemic. Gross Domestic product steadily declined to a negative of 21.5 percent during the first nine months of the 2014/2015 financial year, compared to a neglect growth rate of 27.7 percent during the same period of 2013/2014
